Cell[TextData[{
 "The single blue cell is the lone negative entry, ",
 Cell[BoxData[
  RowBox[{
   StyleBox["W", "TI"], "=", "-", "1", "/", "3"}]], "InlineFormula",
  FontSize->0.9 Inherited,ExpressionUUID->
  "a1cba496-0fd6-49cc-b491-873e0dbfee1f"],
 "; the other eight are the positive ",
 Cell[BoxData[
  RowBox[{"1", "/", "6"}]], "InlineFormula",
  FontSize->0.9 Inherited,ExpressionUUID->
  "44c5aee2-bd8e-41ea-929a-2542a43e8e4a"],
 ". That one blue square is where the state's nonclassicality, its magic, and \
its contextuality all live, and every later section is, in one way or \
another, a way of measuring it."
}], "Text",ExpressionUUID->"9fd51301-1746-4396-872b-06595dd3e018"],

Cell[TextData[{
 "One subtlety deserves a flag rather than a footnote. Gross's clean theorem \
is a statement about ",
 StyleBox["odd",
  FontWeight->"Bold"],
 " dimension. For even ",
 Cell[BoxData[
  StyleBox["d", "TI"]], "InlineFormula",
  FontSize->0.9 Inherited,ExpressionUUID->
  "ef48700e-9de6-4a6a-8ed6-314fe9fa6890"],
 ", and in particular for a qubit, no covariant ",
 Cell[BoxData[
  RowBox[{
   StyleBox["d", "TI"], "\[Times]", 
   StyleBox["d", "TI"]}]], "InlineFormula",
  FontSize->0.9 Inherited,ExpressionUUID->
  "65e3e2dc-dfa2-4b86-a154-8e22b61c29f2"],
 " Wigner function exists, and the standard fix (the one QuantumFramework \
uses) is a Wootters doubling to a ",
 Cell[BoxData[
  RowBox[{"2", 
   StyleBox["d", "TI"], "\[Times]", "2", 
   StyleBox["d", "TI"]}]], "InlineFormula",
  FontSize->0.9 Inherited,ExpressionUUID->
  "5cd3068d-9be7-483d-8872-8695f5ba5e49"],
 " grid. On that grid even the computational qubit state carries negative \
entries, so the \"nonnegative equals stabilizer\" reading is an \
odd-dimensional statement and should not be transported naively to qubits."
}], "Text",ExpressionUUID->"27b557e4-472d-40ec-bff7-28de47fec562"],

Cell[TextData[{
 "Make the failure concrete. Ask the framework for the discrete Wigner \
function of the qubit ",
 Cell[BoxData[
  TemplateBox[{"0"},
   "Ket"]], "InlineFormula",
  FontSize->0.9 Inherited,ExpressionUUID->
  "80bc7435-589c-495b-8bf9-54bad63f342e"],
 ", itself a stabilizer state, and read off the grid size and the most \
negative entry:"
}], "Text",ExpressionUUID->"857daf0b-5a18-4f95-bdbe-4984cf7fc73c"],

Cell[CellGroupData[{

Cell[BoxData[{
 RowBox[{
  RowBox[{"qubit0", " ", "=", " ", 
   RowBox[{"QuantumState", "[", 
    RowBox[{
     RowBox[{"{", 
      RowBox[{"1", ",", " ", "0"}], "}"}], ",", " ", "2"}], "]"}]}], ";"}], "\n", 
 RowBox[{"{", 
  RowBox[{
   RowBox[{"Dimensions", "[", 
    RowBox[{"qubit0", "[", "\"\<QuasiProbability\>\"", "]"}], "]"}], ",", " ", 
   RowBox[{"Min", " ", "@", " ", 
    RowBox[{"Chop", " ", "@", " ", 
     RowBox[{"qubit0", "[", "\"\<QuasiProbability\>\"", "]"}]}]}]}], 
  "}"}]}], "Input",
 CellLabel->
  "In[13]:= ",ExpressionUUID->"be45302f-30b9-404c-9901-9ba32820d2ed"],

Cell[BoxData[
 RowBox[{"{", 
  RowBox[{
   RowBox[{"{", 
    RowBox[{"4", ",", "4"}], "}"}], ",", 
   RowBox[{"-", 
    FractionBox["1", "4"]}]}], "}"}]], "Output",
 CellLabel->
  "Out[13]= ",ExpressionUUID->"18c61b86-fb5d-4ba3-bc45-39a9aa410bf7"]
}, Open  ]],

Cell[TextData[{
 "The table is ",
 Cell[BoxData[
  RowBox[{"4", "\[Times]", "4"}]], "InlineFormula",
  FontSize->0.9 Inherited,ExpressionUUID->
  "516092bb-b77e-4023-9052-44bebfce6e71"],
 ", the ",
 Cell[BoxData[
  RowBox[{"2", 
   StyleBox["d", "TI"], "\[Times]", "2", 
   StyleBox["d", "TI"]}]], "InlineFormula",
  FontSize->0.9 Inherited,ExpressionUUID->
  "7e689e8e-e6b4-4948-a9fe-fbea68b68aa6"],
 " doubling rather than a ",
 Cell[BoxData[
  RowBox[{"2", "\[Times]", "2"}]], "InlineFormula",
  FontSize->0.9 Inherited,ExpressionUUID->
  "002b3ef9-e93b-4969-9a87-08dca1e19287"],
 " grid, and its minimum is ",
 Cell[BoxData[
  RowBox[{"-", "1", "/", "4"}]], "InlineFormula",
  FontSize->0.9 Inherited,ExpressionUUID->
  "f6316762-13a2-4015-89d7-189465bd4891"],
 ": a stabilizer state with a negative Wigner entry. Contrast the qutrit ",
 Cell[BoxData[
  TemplateBox[{"0"},
   "Ket"]], "InlineFormula",
  FontSize->0.9 Inherited,ExpressionUUID->
  "39a033f0-9bfc-40a1-9285-90cb8e8a7fff"],
 " above, which lives on a clean ",
 Cell[BoxData[
  RowBox[{"3", "\[Times]", "3"}]], "InlineFormula",
  FontSize->0.9 Inherited,ExpressionUUID->
  "e3992e80-3c36-4daf-8ed2-fa7cf3b287e9"],
 " grid with minimum ",
 Cell[BoxData["0"], "InlineFormula",
  FontSize->0.9 Inherited,ExpressionUUID->
  "a975b7b9-12ec-4549-9b35-7dc9c4514682"],
 ". This is exactly why Gross's theorem carries the odd-",
 Cell[BoxData[
  StyleBox["d", "TI"]], "InlineFormula",
  FontSize->0.9 Inherited,ExpressionUUID->
  "02030298-244f-488b-8e27-bf602ba65bfd"],
 " hypothesis, and why we run the resource story at ",
 Cell[BoxData[
  RowBox[{
   StyleBox["d", "TI"], "=", "3"}]], "InlineFormula",
  FontSize->0.9 Inherited,ExpressionUUID->
  "7749a61f-17d4-4fd0-87d0-9b1b6e2eda3e"],
 ", where negativity genuinely singles out non-stabilizer states."
}], "Text",ExpressionUUID->"351d4b10-81cb-4554-8dc0-7de4bc4e6f2e"],

Cell["4. Mana: turning negativity into a magic monotone", "Section",ExpressionUUID->"e237a254-d8bf-43f0-8b07-6dfa94ca7146"],

Cell[TextData[{
 "Negativity is a yes-or-no witness; a resource theory wants a number. The \
natural one is the total amount of negativity, and taking its logarithm gives \
",
 StyleBox["mana",
  FontWeight->"Bold"],
 ", defined by Veitch, Mousavian, Gottesman, and Emerson as"
}], "Text",ExpressionUUID->"739128d3-4b8d-485b-aa9a-a804f958049a"],

Cell[BoxData[
 PaneBox[
  RowBox[{
   RowBox[{"\[ScriptCapitalM]", 
    StyleBox["(",
     SpanMaxSize->1], 
    StyleBox["\[Rho]", "TI"], 
    StyleBox[")",
     SpanMaxSize->1], "=", 
    StyleBox["log",
     FontSlant->"Plain"], "\[ThinSpace]", 
    UnderscriptBox["\[Sum]", 
     RowBox[{
      StyleBox["q", "TI"], ",", 
      StyleBox["p", "TI"]}],
     LimitsPositioning->False], 
    StyleBox["|",
     SpanMaxSize->1,
     FontSize->1.2 Inherited], 
    SubscriptBox[
     StyleBox["W", "TI"], 
     StyleBox["\[Rho]", "TI"]], 
    StyleBox["(",
     SpanMaxSize->1], 
    RowBox[{
     StyleBox["q", "TI"], ",", 
     StyleBox["p", "TI"]}], 
    StyleBox[")",
     SpanMaxSize->1], 
    StyleBox["|",
     SpanMaxSize->1,
     FontSize->1.2 Inherited]}], "."}],
  Alignment->Center,
  ImageSize->Full]], "DisplayFormula",ExpressionUUID->"7133c9a4-0241-4ba4-\
9423-bdd20c18e7c0"],

Cell[TextData[{
 "Because a nonnegative Wigner function sums in absolute value to ",
 Cell[BoxData["1"], "InlineFormula",
  FontSize->0.9 Inherited,ExpressionUUID->
  "75db7fe6-510e-4da8-a2a7-9a80673df397"],
 ", mana vanishes on stabilizer states and is strictly positive on states \
with negativity. For odd-dimensional systems (where it is defined, through \
the covariant Wigner function) it is a genuine magic monotone: it does not \
increase under the free stabilizer (Clifford-plus-measurement) operations of \
the resource theory of magic."
}], "Text",ExpressionUUID->"e5e3b4d9-ba4a-4d5b-b678-a45f1a271b0f"],

Cell["\<\
Mana is not a named function in the framework; it is one line built from the \
quasiprobability table, which is exactly the point of having the table. \
Define it and evaluate it on the stabilizer and magic states:\
\>", "Text",ExpressionUUID->"e13bd028-a04d-42b7-87b1-5d34dfc8873d"],

Cell[CellGroupData[{

Cell[BoxData[{
 RowBox[{
  RowBox[{
   RowBox[{"mana", "[", "qs_", "]"}], " ", ":=", " ", 
   RowBox[{"Log", " ", "@", " ", 
    RowBox[{"Total", "[", 
     RowBox[{"Abs", " ", "@", " ", 
      RowBox[{"Flatten", " ", "@", " ", 
       RowBox[{"Chop", " ", "@", " ", 
        RowBox[{"qs", "[", "\"\<QuasiProbability\>\"", "]"}]}]}]}], "]"}]}]}],
   ";"}], "\n", 
 RowBox[{
  RowBox[{"{", 
   RowBox[{
    RowBox[{"mana", "[", "plus", "]"}], ",", " ", 
    RowBox[{"mana", "[", "strange", "]"}]}], "}"}], " ", "//", " ", 
  "Simplify"}]}], "Input",
 CellLabel->
  "In[14]:= ",ExpressionUUID->"33bf77db-722a-473d-831c-48e64b7f4026"],

Cell[BoxData[
 RowBox[{"{", 
  RowBox[{"0", ",", 
   RowBox[{"Log", "[", 
    FractionBox["5", "3"], "]"}]}], "}"}]], "Output",
 CellLabel->
  "Out[14]= ",ExpressionUUID->"dd5a3de2-8498-4020-92dd-ddba83915d58"]
}, Open  ]],

Cell[TextData[{
 "The stabilizer state gives ",
 Cell[BoxData["0"], "InlineFormula",
  FontSize->0.9 Inherited,ExpressionUUID->
  "6ebfdbc2-8aad-4188-a7a8-172b0ed4c600"],
 " and the strange state gives ",
 Cell[BoxData[
  RowBox[{
   StyleBox["log",
    FontSlant->"Plain"], "\[ThinSpace]", 
   StyleBox["(",
    SpanMaxSize->1], 
   RowBox[{"5", "/", "3"}], 
   StyleBox[")",
    SpanMaxSize->1], "\[TildeTilde]", "0.511"}]], "InlineFormula",
  FontSize->0.9 Inherited,ExpressionUUID->
  "c7cebe1e-cb2d-40ac-83be-7ebda23061da"],
 ", which is in fact the maximum mana over all single-qutrit states: the \
strange state is the most magical qutrit pure state by this measure. The same \
object that flagged nonclassicality in the previous section now measures it."
}], "Text",ExpressionUUID->"c731377d-2472-4fb4-af38-450da9378ec5"],

Cell["5. Negativity is the cost of classical simulation", "Section",ExpressionUUID->"9209585d-7307-4a6b-9e49-30752b1d6e15"],

Cell[TextData[{
 "The negative entry in Section 3 is not a philosophical curiosity; it is the \
exponent that controls how hard the state is to simulate on a classical \
computer. The Gottesman-Knill theorem makes stabilizer circuits efficiently \
simulable, and Veitch, Ferrie, Gross, and Emerson extended that reach: for \
odd ",
 Cell[BoxData[
  StyleBox["d", "TI"]], "InlineFormula",
  FontSize->0.9 Inherited,ExpressionUUID->
  "4b175ecd-6ef1-4c5b-a77b-dcebfa79f02b"],
 ", any state and operation with a ",
 StyleBox["nonnegative",
  FontWeight->"Bold"],
 " Wigner function is also efficiently simulable, by sampling the Wigner \
function as if it were an ordinary probability distribution. Pashayan, \
Wallman, and Bartlett showed what happens past that boundary: the sampling \
still works, but the number of samples it needs grows with the total \
negativity, quantitatively as the square of the ",
 Cell[BoxData["1"], "InlineFormula",
  FontSize->0.9 Inherited,ExpressionUUID->
  "f85c7eff-9001-4baa-973b-5d1678382c04"],
 "-norm ",
 Cell[BoxData[
  RowBox[{
   UnderscriptBox["\[Sum]", 
    RowBox[{
     StyleBox["q", "TI"], ",", 
     StyleBox["p", "TI"]}],
    LimitsPositioning->False], GridBox[{
     {
      StyleBox["W", "TI"]}
    },
    GridBoxDividers->{"Columns" -> {True, True}, "Rows" -> {}},
    GridBoxSpacings->{"Columns" -> {{0.15}}}]}]], "InlineFormula",
  FontSize->0.9 Inherited,ExpressionUUID->
  "ea1ae0c1-b015-4c3d-bfa5-a893c34bec23"],
 "."
}], "Text",ExpressionUUID->"ff9b3014-9fee-421d-8c63-a06592f90f78"],

Cell[TextData[{
 "So the resource is negativity, and it has a price tag we can read off. \
Start with the total negativity, the summed weight of the negative part of ",
 Cell[BoxData[
  StyleBox["W", "TI"]], "InlineFormula",
  FontSize->0.9 Inherited,ExpressionUUID->
  "3950b116-4b74-4ffd-a93f-d889aa884774"],
 ":"
}], "Text",ExpressionUUID->"8c41c962-de9a-4ff2-b24e-bb0b054a15d3"],

Cell[CellGroupData[{

Cell[BoxData[{
 RowBox[{
  RowBox[{
   RowBox[{"sumNeg", "[", "qs_", "]"}], " ", ":=", " ", 
   RowBox[{"Total", " ", "@", " ", 
    RowBox[{"Select", "[", 
     RowBox[{
      RowBox[{"Flatten", " ", "@", " ", 
       RowBox[{"Chop", " ", "@", " ", 
        RowBox[{"qs", "[", "\"\<QuasiProbability\>\"", "]"}]}]}], ",", " ", 
      "Negative"}], "]"}]}]}], ";"}], "\n", 
 RowBox[{"{", 
  RowBox[{
   RowBox[{"sumNeg", "[", "plus", "]"}], ",", " ", 
   RowBox[{"sumNeg", "[", "strange", "]"}]}], "}"}]}], "Input",
 CellLabel->
  "In[15]:= ",ExpressionUUID->"ae589a60-7064-4a8c-986a-04a1dc74f36f"],

Cell[BoxData[
 RowBox[{"{", 
  RowBox[{"0", ",", 
   RowBox[{"-", 
    FractionBox["1", "3"]}]}], "}"}]], "Output",
 CellLabel->
  "Out[15]= ",ExpressionUUID->"09c11470-726c-43a6-942a-c662c1c7aa29"]
}, Open  ]],

Cell[TextData[{
 "The stabilizer state contributes ",
 Cell[BoxData["0"], "InlineFormula",
  FontSize->0.9 Inherited,ExpressionUUID->
  "3bc60187-01b9-4c00-bcb2-d7990228af54"],
 " and the strange state ",
 Cell[BoxData[
  RowBox[{"-", "1", "/", "3"}]], "InlineFormula",
  FontSize->0.9 Inherited,ExpressionUUID->
  "3f81c248-44d9-4a39-9d8c-92d26449a67d"],
 ". Turn that into the actual simulation overhead: the relevant quantity is \
the ",
 Cell[BoxData["1"], "InlineFormula",
  FontSize->0.9 Inherited,ExpressionUUID->
  "0d271eec-d46e-40cb-be0d-37d6b4a692bb"],
 "-norm ",
 Cell[BoxData[
  RowBox[{"\|01d4a9", "=", 
   UnderscriptBox["\[Sum]", 
    RowBox[{
     StyleBox["q", "TI"], ",", 
     StyleBox["p", "TI"]}],
    LimitsPositioning->False], GridBox[{
     {
      StyleBox["W", "TI"]}
    },
    GridBoxDividers->{"Columns" -> {True, True}, "Rows" -> {}},
    GridBoxSpacings->{"Columns" -> {{0.15}}}], "=", "1", "+", "2", " ", 
   GridBox[{
     {
      StyleBox["sumNeg",
       FontSlant->"Plain"]}
    },
    GridBoxDividers->{"Columns" -> {True, True}, "Rows" -> {}},
    GridBoxSpacings->{"Columns" -> {{0.15}}}]}]], "InlineFormula",
  FontSize->0.9 Inherited,ExpressionUUID->
  "3546220c-3f71-4d12-a3e5-2553efb69967"],
 ", and the per-copy sampling cost scales as ",
 Cell[BoxData[
  SuperscriptBox["\|01d4a9", "2"]], "InlineFormula",
  FontSize->0.9 Inherited,ExpressionUUID->
  "134a8e86-4f37-4ff8-ae4c-2766fbeb3727"],
 ":"
}], "Text",ExpressionUUID->"005207ee-150e-4e8e-abf1-1cfe5ca29262"],

Cell[CellGroupData[{

Cell[BoxData[{
 RowBox[{
  RowBox[{
   RowBox[{"oneNorm", "[", "qs_", "]"}], " ", ":=", " ", 
   RowBox[{"Total", "[", 
    RowBox[{"Abs", " ", "@", " ", 
     RowBox[{"Flatten", " ", "@", " ", 
      RowBox[{"Chop", " ", "@", " ", 
       RowBox[{"qs", "[", "\"\<QuasiProbability\>\"", "]"}]}]}]}], "]"}]}], 
  ";"}], "\n", 
 RowBox[{
  RowBox[{"{", 
   RowBox[{
    RowBox[{
     RowBox[{"oneNorm", "[", "plus", "]"}], "^", "2"}], ",", " ", 
    RowBox[{
     RowBox[{"oneNorm", "[", "strange", "]"}], "^", "2"}]}], "}"}], " ", "//",
   " ", "Simplify"}]}], "Input",
 CellLabel->
  "In[16]:= ",ExpressionUUID->"6dedcaf5-3874-4a09-bd75-e98b9c693206"],

Cell[BoxData[
 RowBox[{"{", 
  RowBox[{"1", ",", 
   FractionBox["25", "9"]}], "}"}]], "Output",
 CellLabel->
  "Out[16]= ",ExpressionUUID->"1a3f7381-a917-4c16-a17b-48cd9d69b41e"]
}, Open  ]],

Cell[TextData[{
 "The stabilizer state costs a factor ",
 Cell[BoxData["1"], "InlineFormula",
  FontSize->0.9 Inherited,ExpressionUUID->
  "7ee30f82-fe63-4631-8d06-cf6a7c1b67a8"],
 ": it is free, exactly the Gottesman-Knill regime. The strange state costs \
",
 Cell[BoxData[
  RowBox[{
   SuperscriptBox[
    RowBox[{
     StyleBox["(",
      SpanMaxSize->1], 
     RowBox[{"5", "/", "3"}], 
     StyleBox[")",
      SpanMaxSize->1]}], "2"], "=", "25", "/", "9"}]], "InlineFormula",
  FontSize->0.9 Inherited,ExpressionUUID->
  "a1a91031-4da8-479f-84bb-fbbec7988ba8"],
 " per copy. That number is precisely ",
 Cell[BoxData[
  SuperscriptBox[
   StyleBox["e", "TI"], 
   RowBox[{"2", "\[ScriptCapitalM]"}]]], "InlineFormula",
  FontSize->0.9 Inherited,ExpressionUUID->
  "9b1c7c7a-06b7-4a8a-bedd-09dbf20b80ca"],
 " with the mana ",
 Cell[BoxData[
  RowBox[{"\[ScriptCapitalM]", "=", 
   StyleBox["log",
    FontSlant->"Plain"], "\[ThinSpace]", 
   StyleBox["(",
    SpanMaxSize->1], 
   RowBox[{"5", "/", "3"}], 
   StyleBox[")",
    SpanMaxSize->1]}]], "InlineFormula",
  FontSize->0.9 Inherited,ExpressionUUID->
  "0739cb3b-182a-4ce8-9756-4c22ea72b09e"],
 " of Section 4, so mana is literally the per-unit exponent of \
classical-simulation hardness: ",
 Cell[BoxData[
  StyleBox["t", "TI"]], "InlineFormula",
  FontSize->0.9 Inherited,ExpressionUUID->
  "3ee3d99d-c207-45cd-b8a9-2ffd7a46cd29"],
 " copies or magic gates multiply the overhead to ",
 Cell[BoxData[
  SuperscriptBox[
   StyleBox["e", "TI"], 
   RowBox[{"2", 
    StyleBox["t", "TI"], "\[ScriptCapitalM]"}]]], "InlineFormula",
  FontSize->0.9 Inherited,ExpressionUUID->
  "9b1ac4f9-78ca-469b-a1a1-12aca0edda4e"],
 ", and that exponential is where a quantum advantage, if there is one, has \
to live."
}], "Text",ExpressionUUID->"75fcb720-e858-4a64-9afc-58d57a770b3b"],

Cell[TextData[{
 "Two lines keep the accounting honest. First, in this sampling scheme \
nonnegative measurements are free, so the cost must sit in the state. Confirm \
the stabilizer (computational-basis) measurements are nonnegatively \
represented, minimum Wigner entry ",
 Cell[BoxData["0"], "InlineFormula",
  FontSize->0.9 Inherited,ExpressionUUID->
  "45226f45-60bd-407e-a20c-1b6750b3bb62"],
 " over their outcome projectors:"
}], "Text",ExpressionUUID->"a18aa402-7dbc-4614-adf5-5777070ec985"],

Cell[CellGroupData[{

Cell[BoxData[
 RowBox[{"Min", " ", "@", " ", 
  RowBox[{"Chop", " ", "@", " ", 
   RowBox[{"Flatten", " ", "@", " ", 
    RowBox[{"Normal", " ", "@", " ", 
     RowBox[{"Table", "[", 
      RowBox[{
       RowBox[{
        RowBox[{"QuantumState", "[", 
         RowBox[{
          RowBox[{"UnitVector", "[", 
           RowBox[{"3", ",", " ", "k"}], "]"}], ",", " ", "3"}], "]"}], 
        "[", "\"\<QuasiProbability\>\"", "]"}], ",", " ", 
       RowBox[{"{", 
        RowBox[{"k", ",", " ", "3"}], "}"}]}], "]"}]}]}]}]}]], "Input",
 CellLabel->
  "In[17]:= ",ExpressionUUID->"88db2439-6bc4-4b8c-a513-61ee82066860"],

Cell[BoxData["0"], "Output",
 CellLabel->
  "Out[17]= ",ExpressionUUID->"6d19cf40-396d-4198-86c9-6fa180ea58a3"]
}, Open  ]],

Cell[TextData[{
 "The minimum is ",
 Cell[BoxData["0"], "InlineFormula",
  FontSize->0.9 Inherited,ExpressionUUID->
  "c5598d04-a05d-4417-977d-e517e6334f5a"],
 ": every stabilizer effect is nonnegative on the grid, so all the \
negativity, and all the cost, live in the state. Second, this same negativity \
is, by Spekkens' theorem, equivalent to contextuality, the failure of any \
noncontextual model, which is the frame-independent reason it cannot be \
gauged away and the sense in which Howard, Wallman, Veitch, and Emerson say \
contextuality \"supplies the magic.\" The operational content, though, is the \
number above: negativity is what you pay to simulate."
}], "Text",ExpressionUUID->"6c05cd3e-fe7c-4b71-91d7-a66b23840732"],

Cell["6. Changing frames: SIC-POVMs and the Born rule", "Section",ExpressionUUID->"f4f52cad-185d-4a83-9f21-4fa9a06efc68"],

Cell[TextData[{
 "The Wigner phase-point operators are one frame for operator space; they are \
not the only useful one. A ",
 StyleBox["symmetric informationally complete",
  FontWeight->"Bold"],
 " measurement (SIC) is a set of ",
 Cell[BoxData[
  SuperscriptBox[
   StyleBox["d", "TI"], "2"]], "InlineFormula",
  FontSize->0.9 Inherited,ExpressionUUID->
  "34ec0acb-18b1-4ebf-af84-c9e9e5faae42"],
 " subnormalized rank-one effects ",
 Cell[BoxData[
  RowBox[{
   SubscriptBox[
    StyleBox["E", "TI"], 
    StyleBox["i", "TI"]], "=", 
   RowBox[{
    FractionBox["1", 
     StyleBox["d", "TI"]], 
    TemplateBox[{
      SubscriptBox[
       StyleBox["\[Psi]", "TI"], 
       StyleBox["i", "TI"]]},
     "Ket"], 
    TemplateBox[{
      SubscriptBox[
       StyleBox["\[Psi]", "TI"], 
       StyleBox["i", "TI"]]},
     "Bra"]}]}]], "InlineFormula",
  FontSize->0.9 Inherited,ExpressionUUID->
  "98d08864-7f31-4f61-96a4-0b8312a4466d"],
 ", all pairwise equiangular with ",
 Cell[BoxData[
  RowBox[{
   SuperscriptBox[GridBox[{
      {
       TemplateBox[{
         SubscriptBox[
          StyleBox["\[Psi]", "TI"], 
          StyleBox["i", "TI"]], 
         SubscriptBox[
          StyleBox["\[Psi]", "TI"], 
          StyleBox["j", "TI"]]},
        "BraKet"]}
     },
     GridBoxDividers->{"Columns" -> {True, True}, "Rows" -> {}},
     GridBoxSpacings->{"Columns" -> {{0.15}}}], "2"], "=", 
   FractionBox["1", 
    RowBox[{
     StyleBox["d", "TI"], "+", "1"}]]}]], "InlineFormula",
  FontSize->0.9 Inherited,ExpressionUUID->
  "9548b999-d4a1-4436-8fb4-138b0757a63e"],
 " for ",
 Cell[BoxData[
  RowBox[{
   StyleBox["i", "TI"], "\[NotEqual]", 
   StyleBox["j", "TI"]}]], "InlineFormula",
  FontSize->0.9 Inherited,ExpressionUUID->
  "ed4b4622-b9a7-4b4c-aeb1-28e3f872e129"],
 ", that resolve the identity and so form a minimal informationally complete \
measurement. SICs are the frame at the center of the QBist reconstruction of \
quantum mechanics, where the Born rule reappears as a coherence condition \
relating the probabilities of a SIC to those of any other measurement."
}], "Text",ExpressionUUID->"c122f637-fad1-4a32-9e9f-a316cedb2e6a"],

Cell["\<\
The framework ships the standard SICs as named measurements. Build the qutrit \
Hesse SIC, the most symmetric of the Weyl-Heisenberg-covariant qutrit SICs \
(its enlarged symmetry group is tied to the Hesse configuration of inflection \
points on an elliptic curve), and confirm it resolves the identity, the \
defining property of a POVM:\
\>", "Text",ExpressionUUID->"152c00cc-28df-4275-b0ae-d035e506f5cf"],

Cell[CellGroupData[{

Cell[BoxData[{
 RowBox[{
  RowBox[{"hesse", " ", "=", " ", 
   RowBox[{"QuantumMeasurementOperator", "[", 
    RowBox[{"\"\<HesseSICPOVM\>\"", "[", "]"}], "]"}]}], ";"}], "\n", 
 RowBox[{
  RowBox[{"elements", " ", "=", " ", 
   RowBox[{"hesse", "[", "\"\<POVMElements\>\"", "]"}]}], ";"}], "\n", 
 RowBox[{"{", 
  RowBox[{
   RowBox[{"Length", "[", "elements", "]"}], ",", " ", 
   RowBox[{
    RowBox[{"Chop", "[", 
     RowBox[{"N", "[", 
      RowBox[{
       RowBox[{"Total", "[", "elements", "]"}], " ", "-", " ", 
       RowBox[{"IdentityMatrix", "[", "3", "]"}]}], "]"}], "]"}], " ", "//", 
    " ", "MatrixForm"}]}], "}"}]}], "Input",
 CellLabel->
  "In[18]:= ",ExpressionUUID->"73870994-d7a6-45fc-aa2d-10e3f40bab43"],

Cell[BoxData[
 RowBox[{"{", 
  RowBox[{"9", ",", 
   TagBox[
    RowBox[{"(", "\[NoBreak]", GridBox[{
       {"0", "0", "0"},
       {"0", "0", "0"},
       {"0", "0", "0"}
      },
      GridBoxAlignment->{"Columns" -> {{Center}}, "Rows" -> {{Baseline}}},
      GridBoxSpacings->{"Columns" -> {
          Offset[0.27999999999999997`], {
           Offset[0.7]}, 
          Offset[0.27999999999999997`]}, "Rows" -> {
          Offset[0.2], {
           Offset[0.4]}, 
          Offset[0.2]}}], "\[NoBreak]", ")"}],
    Function[BoxForm`e$, 
     MatrixForm[BoxForm`e$]]]}], "}"}]], "Output",
 CellLabel->
  "Out[18]= ",ExpressionUUID->"db74003e-28a3-4297-b9a6-ce9968de2ffb"]
}, Open  ]],

Cell[TextData[{
 "There are ",
 Cell[BoxData[
  RowBox[{"9", "=", 
   SuperscriptBox[
    StyleBox["d", "TI"], "2"]}]], "InlineFormula",
  FontSize->0.9 Inherited,ExpressionUUID->
  "a1182cf2-ddd9-4a66-8026-1e0d634e6fdb"],
 " elements and their sum is the identity. The measurement is informationally \
complete: the nine outcome probabilities carry the eight independent real \
parameters of a qutrit density matrix (the ninth constraint is \
normalization), so the state can be reconstructed from SIC statistics alone."
}], "Text",ExpressionUUID->"b1ae9dd5-b3ef-4db9-8981-2b169b649e2f"],

Cell[TextData[{
 "Applying the SIC to a state gives its outcome distribution directly. There \
is a pleasing coincidence to exploit: the Hesse SIC's fiducial vector is \
exactly the strange state ",
 Cell[BoxData[
  RowBox[{
   FractionBox["1", 
    SqrtBox["2"]], 
   StyleBox["(",
    SpanMaxSize->1], 
   RowBox[{
    RowBox[{"0", ",", "1"}], ",", 
    RowBox[{"-", "1"}]}], 
   StyleBox[")",
    SpanMaxSize->1]}]], "InlineFormula",
  FontSize->0.9 Inherited,ExpressionUUID->
  "5c0c00bf-ffbd-4f51-a09a-e39419797626"],
 " from Section 3, so the most magical qutrit state is the fiducial of the \
most symmetric qutrit SIC. Compute the Hesse-SIC probabilities for the \
strange state, that is, of the SIC's own fiducial:"
}], "Text",ExpressionUUID->"7c7579dc-f77d-4947-8ce7-32bc1d021528"],

Cell[CellGroupData[{

Cell[BoxData[
 RowBox[{"Simplify", " ", "@", " ", 
  RowBox[{
   RowBox[{"hesse", "[", "strange", "]"}], "[", "\"\<ProbabilitiesList\>\"", 
   "]"}]}]], "Input",
 CellLabel->
  "In[19]:= ",ExpressionUUID->"6775514b-6cd0-4700-9452-fc13e4ee1694"],

Cell[BoxData[
 RowBox[{"{", 
  RowBox[{
   FractionBox["1", "3"], ",", 
   FractionBox["1", "12"], ",", 
   FractionBox["1", "12"], ",", 
   FractionBox["1", "12"], ",", 
   FractionBox["1", "12"], ",", 
   FractionBox["1", "12"], ",", 
   FractionBox["1", "12"], ",", 
   FractionBox["1", "12"], ",", 
   FractionBox["1", "12"]}], "}"}]], "Output",
 CellLabel->
  "Out[19]= ",ExpressionUUID->"dee0d070-38d5-41ba-8bab-ebc91690cd88"]
}, Open  ]],

Cell[TextData[{
 "The result is one bright outcome ",
 Cell[BoxData[
  RowBox[{"1", "/", 
   StyleBox["d", "TI"], "=", "1", "/", "3"}]], "InlineFormula",
  FontSize->0.9 Inherited,ExpressionUUID->
  "f1308aa3-08a9-4965-aeda-f27a8617a676"],
 " and eight equal dim ones ",
 Cell[BoxData[
  RowBox[{"1", "/", 
   StyleBox["(",
    SpanMaxSize->1], 
   RowBox[{
    StyleBox["d", "TI"], 
    StyleBox["(",
     SpanMaxSize->1], 
    RowBox[{
     StyleBox["d", "TI"], "+", "1"}], 
    StyleBox[")",
     SpanMaxSize->1]}], 
   StyleBox[")",
    SpanMaxSize->1], "=", "1", "/", "12"}]], "InlineFormula",
  FontSize->0.9 Inherited,ExpressionUUID->
  "a18384f0-9307-4be0-b7b9-ea8cb639fefe"],
 ", exactly the signature of a SIC measured on its own fiducial. More \
generally these ",
 Cell[BoxData[
  SuperscriptBox[
   StyleBox["d", "TI"], "2"]], "InlineFormula",
  FontSize->0.9 Inherited,ExpressionUUID->
  "f26c716a-8855-4d0b-bf29-7dbefad16328"],
 " numbers are a complete, symmetric fingerprint of any state, the \"Bureau \
of Standards\" reference measurement in the QBist account."
}], "Text",ExpressionUUID->"f5695769-2e18-40e5-9ceb-80f98fc3beee"],

Cell[TextData[{
 "Why care about a SIC in particular? Because it is the most efficient single \
measurement for learning an unknown state. Its ",
 Cell[BoxData[
  SuperscriptBox[
   StyleBox["d", "TI"], "2"]], "InlineFormula",
  FontSize->0.9 Inherited,ExpressionUUID->
  "cbd82d10-671b-4579-8417-87b25dd85dd9"],
 " outcomes are the minimum for informational completeness, and its symmetry \
makes the linear reconstruction optimally robust to noise (Scott). \
Concretely, the state is a simple linear function of the SIC probabilities,"
}], "Text",ExpressionUUID->"a368ba6b-8637-4b69-9fc3-d9a6d1787761"],

Cell[BoxData[
 PaneBox[
  RowBox[{
   RowBox[{
    StyleBox["\[Rho]", "TI"], "=", 
    StyleBox["d", "TI"], 
    StyleBox["(",
     SpanMaxSize->1], 
    RowBox[{
     StyleBox["d", "TI"], "+", "1"}], 
    StyleBox[")",
     SpanMaxSize->1], 
    UnderscriptBox["\[Sum]", 
     StyleBox["i", "TI"],
     LimitsPositioning->False], 
    SubscriptBox[
     StyleBox["p", "TI"], 
     StyleBox["i", "TI"]], " ", 
    SubscriptBox[
     StyleBox["E", "TI"], 
     StyleBox["i", "TI"]], "-", 
    StyleBox["I", "TI"]}], ","}],
  Alignment->Center,
  ImageSize->Full]], "DisplayFormula",ExpressionUUID->"f52d0f46-3750-483d-\
98fb-ef60629cd52f"],

Cell[TextData[{
 "so the numbers a SIC measurement returns are exactly the coordinates of ",
 Cell[BoxData[
  StyleBox["\[Rho]", "TI"]], "InlineFormula",
  FontSize->0.9 Inherited,ExpressionUUID->
  "43071f87-7f33-4d64-a0bb-93862786345a"],
 ". Reconstruct the strange state from its own Hesse-SIC statistics:"
}], "Text",ExpressionUUID->"773bbec7-5557-41ae-b3df-b349246bfa10"],

Cell[CellGroupData[{

Cell[BoxData[{
 RowBox[{
  RowBox[{"p", " ", "=", " ", 
   RowBox[{
    RowBox[{"hesse", "[", "strange", "]"}], "[", "\"\<ProbabilitiesList\>\"", 
    "]"}]}], ";"}], "\n", 
 RowBox[{
  RowBox[{"Ei", " ", "=", " ", 
   RowBox[{"hesse", "[", "\"\<POVMElements\>\"", "]"}]}], ";"}], "\n", 
 RowBox[{
  RowBox[{"\[Rho]rec", " ", "=", " ", 
   RowBox[{
    RowBox[{"d", " ", 
     RowBox[{"(", 
      RowBox[{"d", " ", "+", " ", "1"}], ")"}], " ", 
     RowBox[{"Sum", "[", 
      RowBox[{
       RowBox[{
        RowBox[{"p", "[", 
         RowBox[{"[", "i", "]"}], "]"}], " ", 
        RowBox[{"Ei", "[", 
         RowBox[{"[", "i", "]"}], "]"}]}], ",", " ", 
       RowBox[{"{", 
        RowBox[{"i", ",", " ", 
         RowBox[{"d", "^", "2"}]}], "}"}]}], "]"}]}], " ", "-", " ", 
    RowBox[{"IdentityMatrix", "[", "d", "]"}]}]}], ";"}], "\n", 
 RowBox[{"Simplify", "[", 
  RowBox[{"\[Rho]rec", " ", "==", " ", 
   RowBox[{"strange", "[", "\"\<DensityMatrix\>\"", "]"}]}], "]"}]}], "Input",\

 CellLabel->
  "In[20]:= ",ExpressionUUID->"cf8eec80-a791-4853-b50b-58fedd8e9706"],

Cell[BoxData["True"], "Output",
 CellLabel->
  "Out[20]= ",ExpressionUUID->"364aa757-042d-4214-b0f6-0c82139a03bb"]
}, Open  ]],

Cell[TextData[{
 Cell[BoxData["True"], "InlineFormula",
  FontSize->0.9 Inherited,ExpressionUUID->
  "257aa2d7-c436-4c2b-bafd-8b910c5e3a92"],
 ": the nine probabilities a single SIC measurement produces are enough to \
rebuild the entire density matrix, and no smaller measurement could. That is \
the operational reason SICs matter, they are optimal quantum-state tomography \
in one device, and it is why they have been realized in the laboratory for \
exactly that purpose."
}], "Text",ExpressionUUID->"e3aa6a30-34e6-4bfc-8da0-2f8a82b41ee1"],

Cell["\<\
7. Minimal informationally complete measurements more generally\
\>", "Section",ExpressionUUID->"66e6de10-fc04-4b4e-99e4-d94cbfb0b15c"],

Cell[TextData[{
 "A SIC is the most symmetric member of a broader family: the ",
 StyleBox["minimal informationally complete",
  FontWeight->"Bold"],
 " measurements (MICs), any ",
 Cell[BoxData[
  SuperscriptBox[
   StyleBox["d", "TI"], "2"]], "InlineFormula",
  FontSize->0.9 Inherited,ExpressionUUID->
  "007af1d1-e3ee-400e-a3ee-f343a3e46f65"],
 " operators that resolve the identity and span operator space. DeBrota, \
Fuchs, and Stacey study these as the natural reference frames for a \
probabilistic representation of quantum theory, and the discrete Wigner \
function itself can be recovered from a suitable (Weyl-Heisenberg-covariant) \
MIC via the DeBrota-Stacey construction. The framework builds several: a MIC \
from the Gell-Mann basis, random MICs, and the Wigner-MIC that ties this \
section back to Section 2."
}], "Text",ExpressionUUID->"ac9fab76-c42b-4838-a0c0-7f0a70ba442a"],

Cell["\<\
Build the Gell-Mann MIC for the qutrit and confirm it too is a valid \
informationally complete POVM:\
\>", "Text",ExpressionUUID->"dc37db90-b834-4cfb-b866-3ae8cb2c1dc0"],

Cell[CellGroupData[{

Cell[BoxData[{
 RowBox[{
  RowBox[{"gm", " ", "=", " ", 
   RowBox[{"QuantumMeasurementOperator", "[", 
    RowBox[{"\"\<GellMannMICPOVM\>\"", "[", "3", "]"}], "]"}]}], 
  ";"}], "\n", 
 RowBox[{
  RowBox[{"els", " ", "=", " ", 
   RowBox[{"gm", "[", "\"\<POVMElements\>\"", "]"}]}], ";"}], "\n", 
 RowBox[{"{", 
  RowBox[{
   RowBox[{"Length", "[", "els", "]"}], ",", " ", 
   RowBox[{
    RowBox[{"Chop", "[", 
     RowBox[{"N", "[", 
      RowBox[{
       RowBox[{"Total", "[", "els", "]"}], " ", "-", " ", 
       RowBox[{"IdentityMatrix", "[", "3", "]"}]}], "]"}], "]"}], " ", "//", 
    " ", "MatrixForm"}]}], "}"}]}], "Input",
 CellLabel->
  "In[21]:= ",ExpressionUUID->"174b369f-f110-4b1d-a0c3-f574a9e76156"],

Cell[BoxData[
 RowBox[{"{", 
  RowBox[{"9", ",", 
   TagBox[
    RowBox[{"(", "\[NoBreak]", GridBox[{
       {"0", "0", "0"},
       {"0", "0", "0"},
       {"0", "0", "0"}
      },
      GridBoxAlignment->{"Columns" -> {{Center}}, "Rows" -> {{Baseline}}},
      GridBoxSpacings->{"Columns" -> {
          Offset[0.27999999999999997`], {
           Offset[0.7]}, 
          Offset[0.27999999999999997`]}, "Rows" -> {
          Offset[0.2], {
           Offset[0.4]}, 
          Offset[0.2]}}], "\[NoBreak]", ")"}],
    Function[BoxForm`e$, 
     MatrixForm[BoxForm`e$]]]}], "}"}]], "Output",
 CellLabel->
  "Out[21]= ",ExpressionUUID->"dd584fb1-3082-488b-84d6-3f4fbfd23baf"]
}, Open  ]],

Cell[TextData[{
 "Nine elements summing to the identity: a MIC that is informationally \
complete without being symmetric. The lesson is that \"informationally \
complete\" is the load-bearing property and symmetry is a bonus that the SIC \
adds on top. This is why MICs, not SICs, are what a real laboratory works \
with: a physical detector is almost never a perfect SIC, but as long as it is \
informationally complete the same linear inversion ",
 Cell[BoxData[
  RowBox[{
   StyleBox["\[Rho]", "TI"], "=", 
   UnderscriptBox["\[Sum]", 
    StyleBox["i", "TI"],
    LimitsPositioning->False], 
   SubscriptBox[
    StyleBox["p", "TI"], 
    StyleBox["i", "TI"]], 
   SubscriptBox[
    StyleBox["D", "TI"], 
    StyleBox["i", "TI"]]}]], "InlineFormula",
  FontSize->0.9 Inherited,ExpressionUUID->
  "2654d8b0-43b9-4c61-9597-1a148162bfc9"],
 " (now with the dual frame ",
 Cell[BoxData[
  SubscriptBox[
   StyleBox["D", "TI"], 
   StyleBox["i", "TI"]]], "InlineFormula",
  FontSize->0.9 Inherited,ExpressionUUID->
  "8932f51e-01e5-4f67-8662-f22693a2c748"],
 " of a generic MIC rather than the tidy SIC formula) reconstructs the state, \
just with a less favorable error scaling. The SIC is the optimum you design \
toward; a MIC is the apparatus you actually have."
}], "Text",ExpressionUUID->"55568316-485c-40f3-8ce1-710fcda8e957"],

Cell["8. Mutually unbiased bases", "Section",ExpressionUUID->"a79e589b-64fb-4031-b76a-8b55072ad6bd"],

Cell[TextData[{
 "Where a SIC is a single optimal measurement, ",
 StyleBox["mutually unbiased bases",
  FontWeight->"Bold"],
 " are an optimal ",
 StyleBox["collection", "TI"],
 " of measurements. Two orthonormal bases are unbiased when a definite state \
in one is completely uncertain in the other, ",
 Cell[BoxData[
  RowBox[{
   SuperscriptBox[GridBox[{
      {
       TemplateBox[{
         SubscriptBox[
          StyleBox["a", "TI"], 
          StyleBox["i", "TI"]], 
         SubscriptBox[
          StyleBox["b", "TI"], 
          StyleBox["j", "TI"]]},
        "BraKet"]}
     },
     GridBoxDividers->{"Columns" -> {True, True}, "Rows" -> {}},
     GridBoxSpacings->{"Columns" -> {{0.15}}}], "2"], "=", "1", "/", 
   StyleBox["d", "TI"]}]], "InlineFormula",
  FontSize->0.9 Inherited,ExpressionUUID->
  "1183f915-5162-4a5d-a43f-5d0aa210fcb5"],
 " for all ",
 Cell[BoxData[
  RowBox[{
   StyleBox["i", "TI"], ",", 
   StyleBox["j", "TI"]}]], "InlineFormula",
  FontSize->0.9 Inherited,ExpressionUUID->
  "2bf689d0-9d42-4072-8a0a-0265cdbfeb70"],
 ", so that measuring in the wrong basis yields no information. For \
prime-power ",
 Cell[BoxData[
  StyleBox["d", "TI"]], "InlineFormula",
  FontSize->0.9 Inherited,ExpressionUUID->
  "846663a1-0e22-4595-b58a-d9fbf4861a35"],
 " there are ",
 Cell[BoxData[
  RowBox[{
   StyleBox["d", "TI"], "+", "1"}]], "InlineFormula",
  FontSize->0.9 Inherited,ExpressionUUID->
  "e7bca646-0975-40a5-b282-41f0a1131cd9"],
 " such bases, the maximal set, and they give the most efficient state \
tomography (the optimality is the Wootters-Fields result; the explicit prime-",
 Cell[BoxData[
  StyleBox["d", "TI"]], "InlineFormula",
  FontSize->0.9 Inherited,ExpressionUUID->
  "81a723f7-a607-4d93-8103-4f520ad38fec"],
 " construction is Ivanovic's). The framework provides the Ivanovic \
construction directly."
}], "Text",ExpressionUUID->"2ef4332c-55b6-47e9-81b4-5298d5e92800"],

Cell[TextData[{
 "Build one Ivanovic basis for ",
 Cell[BoxData[
  RowBox[{
   StyleBox["d", "TI"], "=", "3"}]], "InlineFormula",
  FontSize->0.9 Inherited,ExpressionUUID->
  "d903f867-eee6-464b-9a78-1c03165aebe4"],
 " and check that it is unbiased with respect to the computational basis:"
}], "Text",ExpressionUUID->"27c02aac-6399-4459-9067-e0654f16b457"],

Cell[CellGroupData[{

Cell[BoxData[{
 RowBox[{
  RowBox[{"mub", " ", "=", " ", 
   RowBox[{"QuditBasis", "[", 
    RowBox[{"\"\<Ivanovic\>\"", "[", 
     RowBox[{"3", ",", " ", "1"}], "]"}], "]"}]}], ";"}], "\n", 
 RowBox[{
  RowBox[{
   RowBox[{"Chop", " ", "@", " ", 
    RowBox[{"Abs", "[", 
     RowBox[{"mub", "[", "\"\<Matrix\>\"", "]"}], "]"}]}], "^", "2"}], " ", "//",
   " ", "MatrixForm"}]}], "Input",
 CellLabel->
  "In[22]:= ",ExpressionUUID->"62ed200c-93c7-4b21-90fd-c0e77eebed37"],

Cell[BoxData[
 TagBox[
  RowBox[{"(", "\[NoBreak]", GridBox[{
     {
      FractionBox["1", "3"], 
      FractionBox["1", "3"], 
      FractionBox["1", "3"]},
     {
      FractionBox["1", "3"], 
      FractionBox["1", "3"], 
      FractionBox["1", "3"]},
     {
      FractionBox["1", "3"], 
      FractionBox["1", "3"], 
      FractionBox["1", "3"]}
    },
    GridBoxAlignment->{"Columns" -> {{Center}}, "Rows" -> {{Baseline}}},
    GridBoxSpacings->{"Columns" -> {
        Offset[0.27999999999999997`], {
         Offset[0.7]}, 
        Offset[0.27999999999999997`]}, "Rows" -> {
        Offset[0.2], {
         Offset[0.4]}, 
        Offset[0.2]}}], "\[NoBreak]", ")"}],
  Function[BoxForm`e$, 
   MatrixForm[
   SparseArray[
    Automatic, {3, 3}, 0, {
     1, {{0, 3, 6, 9}, {{1}, {2}, {3}, {1}, {2}, {3}, {1}, {2}, {3}}}, {
      Rational[1, 3], Rational[1, 3], Rational[1, 3], Rational[1, 3], 
       Rational[1, 3], Rational[1, 3], Rational[1, 3], Rational[1, 3], 
       Rational[1, 3]}}]]]]], "Output",
 CellLabel->
  "Out[22]= ",ExpressionUUID->"23132e89-3c60-4a8f-a662-2ad831531843"]
}, Open  ]],

Cell[TextData[{
 "Every entry is ",
 Cell[BoxData[
  RowBox[{"1", "/", "3"}]], "InlineFormula",
  FontSize->0.9 Inherited,ExpressionUUID->
  "c7573227-f110-40c1-b4aa-be111b2888a3"],
 ": a state sharp in the computational basis is maximally spread over the \
Ivanovic basis. These are the finite-dimensional embodiment of \
complementarity."
}], "Text",ExpressionUUID->"4f2b83bc-91b8-49be-8634-e2de584a227b"],

Cell[TextData[{
 "The payoff is twofold, and both halves are practical. For tomography, the \
",
 Cell[BoxData[
  RowBox[{
   StyleBox["d", "TI"], "+", "1"}]], "InlineFormula",
  FontSize->0.9 Inherited,ExpressionUUID->
  "92dea9c5-39e6-48ee-ad10-96bddec215e9"],
 " mutually unbiased bases are the most efficient set of projective \
measurements: they read out the ",
 Cell[BoxData[
  RowBox[{
   SuperscriptBox[
    StyleBox["d", "TI"], "2"], "-", "1"}]], "InlineFormula",
  FontSize->0.9 Inherited,ExpressionUUID->
  "963a6b65-3904-4ab2-89fb-b979a4d414d5"],
 " parameters of a state with the fewest settings and the smallest \
statistical error, the basis-measurement counterpart of what a SIC does in \
one shot. For cryptography, complementarity ",
 StyleBox["is", "TI"],
 " the security of quantum key distribution: an eavesdropper who guesses the \
wrong basis learns nothing, precisely the flat ",
 Cell[BoxData[
  RowBox[{"1", "/", 
   StyleBox["d", "TI"]}]], "InlineFormula",
  FontSize->0.9 Inherited,ExpressionUUID->
  "d0df1e02-ea6e-42ab-a3f3-90381a8f1a7b"],
 " we just computed, so encoding key bits in mutually unbiased bases (BB84 \
for the qubit, its qudit generalizations here) makes any interception show up \
as errors. The ",
 Cell[BoxData[
  RowBox[{"1", "/", "3"}]], "InlineFormula",
  FontSize->0.9 Inherited,ExpressionUUID->
  "51cceb73-f8d5-4030-94eb-c5463d807c4d"],
 " in that table is not a curiosity; it is the reason MUBs are the workhorse \
of both quantum tomography and quantum key distribution."
}], "Text",ExpressionUUID->"9cba489d-a736-40ba-a237-8788d09ff41a"],

Cell["9. The Weyl transform: from phase space back to operators", "Section",ExpressionUUID->"8d7f106d-0e53-4840-9f77-58e7c22ccb26"],

Cell[TextData[{
 "Everything so far has pushed states into a phase-space representation. The \
inverse map is the ",
 StyleBox["Weyl transform",
  FontWeight->"Bold"],
 ", which reconstructs an operator from its phase-space symbol; the Wigner \
and Weyl transforms are the two directions of the finite Weyl-Wigner \
correspondence. Because the phase-point operators are a complete orthogonal \
basis, the round trip is exact: transforming a state to phase space and back \
returns the original state."
}], "Text",ExpressionUUID->"65c33fd7-977d-4a56-9904-171bf1245b28"],

Cell["Confirm the round trip on the strange state:", "Text",ExpressionUUID->"86b18133-758d-4b60-b860-ec325446baaa"],

Cell[CellGroupData[{

Cell[BoxData[{
 RowBox[{
  RowBox[{"back", " ", "=", " ", 
   RowBox[{"QuantumWeylTransform", " ", "@", " ", 
    RowBox[{"QuantumWignerTransform", "[", "strange", "]"}]}]}], 
  ";"}], "\n", 
 RowBox[{
  RowBox[{"FullSimplify", "[", 
   RowBox[{"ComplexExpand", "[", 
    RowBox[{"Normal", "[", 
     RowBox[{
      RowBox[{"back", "[", "\"\<DensityMatrix\>\"", "]"}], " ", "-", " ", 
      RowBox[{"strange", "[", "\"\<DensityMatrix\>\"", "]"}]}], "]"}], "]"}], 
   "]"}], " ", "//", " ", "MatrixForm"}]}], "Input",
 CellLabel->
  "In[23]:= ",ExpressionUUID->"226d6f69-2a14-4b55-a5b0-10096f905e82"],

Cell[BoxData[
 TagBox[
  RowBox[{"(", "\[NoBreak]", GridBox[{
     {"0", "0", "0"},
     {"0", "0", "0"},
     {"0", "0", "0"}
    },
    GridBoxAlignment->{"Columns" -> {{Center}}, "Rows" -> {{Baseline}}},
    GridBoxSpacings->{"Columns" -> {
        Offset[0.27999999999999997`], {
         Offset[0.7]}, 
        Offset[0.27999999999999997`]}, "Rows" -> {
        Offset[0.2], {
         Offset[0.4]}, 
        Offset[0.2]}}], "\[NoBreak]", ")"}],
  Function[BoxForm`e$, 
   MatrixForm[BoxForm`e$]]]], "Output",
 CellLabel->
  "Out[23]= ",ExpressionUUID->"0f856051-a4e0-4dcf-ac3e-d0b0cc98930e"]
}, Open  ]],

Cell[TextData[{
 "The difference is the zero matrix. The entries come back as exact cube-root \
surds inside a sparse array, so we ",
 Cell[BoxData["Normal"], "InlineFormula",
  FontSize->0.9 Inherited,ExpressionUUID->
  "860c5ff8-22fe-4545-b3b4-e9d169a1c598"],
 "-unpack and ",
 Cell[BoxData["ComplexExpand"], "InlineFormula",
  FontSize->0.9 Inherited,ExpressionUUID->
  "2baf6fc6-8be0-47ef-810d-6b775cfc46d8"],
 " before ",
 Cell[BoxData["FullSimplify"], "InlineFormula",
  FontSize->0.9 Inherited,ExpressionUUID->
  "364a1b5a-a6ea-4a96-bce7-94c1c5a53298"],
 " can cancel them (plain ",
 Cell[BoxData["Chop"], "InlineFormula",
  FontSize->0.9 Inherited,ExpressionUUID->
  "2e4d8134-2d13-4f84-a6a1-2a2027793532"],
 " does not reach inside the structured entries). The phase-space picture \
loses nothing; it is a faithful, invertible re-encoding of the state, which \
is what licenses us to do physics in it."
}], "Text",ExpressionUUID->"fb5cf16a-206e-42bb-ba92-86f229de0f6a"],

Cell["\<\
That invertibility is the whole license for the phase-space program. The \
classical-simulation sampling of Section 5 is only valid because the encoding \
loses nothing, and the dynamics of the next section will run entirely on the \
grid and return to a density matrix through exactly this transform. The Weyl \
map is the return ticket that turns phase space from a one-way picture into a \
working computational tool.\
\>", "Text",ExpressionUUID->"4d2ac92f-43f7-4caa-8656-53bd2c10e518"],

Cell["10. Dynamics: the transition-rate generator", "Section",ExpressionUUID->"b5127bfe-6ce0-49a1-9146-38839461fbcf"],

Cell[TextData[{
 "The deepest payoff is that phase space is not just a static portrait but a \
place to do dynamics. Braasch and Wootters showed that continuous-time \
evolution of the discrete Wigner function is governed by a ",
 StyleBox["transition-rate generator",
  FontWeight->"Bold"],
 ": writing the Wigner function as a vector ",
 Cell[BoxData[
  StyleBox["W", "TI"]], "InlineFormula",
  FontSize->0.9 Inherited,ExpressionUUID->
  "81388822-853d-4fec-a2d7-032396d4585e"],
 ", its evolution obeys ",
 Cell[BoxData[
  RowBox[{
   OverscriptBox[
    StyleBox["W", "TI"], "."], "=", 
   StyleBox["R", "TI"], " ", 
   StyleBox["W", "TI"]}]], "InlineFormula",
  FontSize->0.9 Inherited,ExpressionUUID->
  "ea08be48-0c8f-41db-a116-3fabfbc35dd5"],
 ", where the rate matrix ",
 Cell[BoxData[
  StyleBox["R", "TI"]], "InlineFormula",
  FontSize->0.9 Inherited,ExpressionUUID->
  "5cd28b21-e175-4f64-92dc-4997f7455bf8"],
 " is obtained by expanding the Hamiltonian in displacement operators, which \
amounts to taking the phase-space symbol of ",
 Cell[BoxData[
  StyleBox["H", "TI"]], "InlineFormula",
  FontSize->0.9 Inherited,ExpressionUUID->
  "f07c5f69-1c4d-459e-b069-e9ae39ffe890"],
 " and dividing out the unitary ",
 Cell[BoxData[
  StyleBox["i", "TI"]], "InlineFormula",
  FontSize->0.9 Inherited,ExpressionUUID->
  "24b73362-70e8-4873-9bff-98302974444b"],
 ". QuantumFramework computes exactly this generator through ",
 Cell[BoxData["HamiltonianTransitionRate"], "InlineFormula",
  FontSize->0.9 Inherited,ExpressionUUID->
  "5bb9c124-bcf1-42f2-a21e-75d9e9951797"],
 "."
}], "Text",ExpressionUUID->"51ea382a-2dbf-4df4-b628-843e0008f0b6"],

Cell[TextData[{
 "Build the transition-rate matrix for a Hermitian qutrit Hamiltonian, the \
nearest-neighbor hopping ",
 Cell[BoxData[
  RowBox[{
   StyleBox["H", "TI"], "=", 
   StyleBox["X", "TI"], "+", 
   SuperscriptBox[
    StyleBox["X", "TI"], "\[Dagger]"]}]], "InlineFormula",
  FontSize->0.9 Inherited,ExpressionUUID->
  "390b6c7d-8c82-47f7-90ff-38b31205911b"],
 " on the three-site ring:"
}], "Text",ExpressionUUID->"c2bc9e16-1177-4d94-9b54-1fa3ceca34f3"],

Cell[CellGroupData[{

Cell[BoxData[{
 RowBox[{
  RowBox[{"Hq", " ", "=", " ", 
   RowBox[{"QuantumOperator", "[", 
    RowBox[{
     RowBox[{"X", " ", "+", " ", 
      RowBox[{"ConjugateTranspose", "[", "X", "]"}]}], ",", " ", 
     RowBox[{"{", "1", "}"}]}], "]"}]}], ";"}], "\n", 
 RowBox[{
  RowBox[{"rate", " ", "=", " ", 
   RowBox[{"HamiltonianTransitionRate", "[", "Hq", "]"}]}], ";"}], "\n", 
 RowBox[{"{", 
  RowBox[{
   RowBox[{"Dimensions", "[", "rate", "]"}], ",", " ", 
   RowBox[{"Chop", " ", "@", " ", 
    RowBox[{"Max", " ", "@", " ", 
     RowBox[{"Abs", " ", "@", " ", 
      RowBox[{"Im", " ", "@", " ", "rate"}]}]}]}]}], "}"}]}], "Input",
 CellLabel->
  "In[24]:= ",ExpressionUUID->"17524ea7-129d-4fd2-ac48-236510376cb9"],

Cell[BoxData[
 RowBox[{"{", 
  RowBox[{
   RowBox[{"{", 
    RowBox[{"9", ",", "9"}], "}"}], ",", "0"}], "}"}]], "Output",
 CellLabel->
  "Out[24]= ",ExpressionUUID->"83f0b892-8650-4a24-9987-262c2191b75a"]
}, Open  ]],

Cell[TextData[{
 "The generator is a ",
 Cell[BoxData[
  RowBox[{"9", "\[Times]", "9"}]], "InlineFormula",
  FontSize->0.9 Inherited,ExpressionUUID->
  "6bb1b58f-ec75-454d-a637-bc1392f3e90c"],
 " matrix acting on the nine-component Wigner vector of the qutrit: the \
discrete-phase-space analogue of the Liouville operator that pushes a \
classical distribution around phase space. For this real-symmetric ",
 Cell[BoxData[
  StyleBox["H", "TI"]], "InlineFormula",
  FontSize->0.9 Inherited,ExpressionUUID->
  "90e78c5c-a856-476d-bf30-4f0460ecb7fe"],
 " the generator is real (the second entry is ",
 Cell[BoxData["0"], "InlineFormula",
  FontSize->0.9 Inherited,ExpressionUUID->
  "0bef65c5-68be-4efb-8bff-d8f8149ae310"],
 "), the special case in which its imaginary part vanishes. Reality alone \
does not make ",
 Cell[BoxData[
  StyleBox["R", "TI"]], "InlineFormula",
  FontSize->0.9 Inherited,ExpressionUUID->
  "2a49ad81-a154-4ba0-af4b-37dcbe522862"],
 " a classical stochastic generator, though: Braasch and Wootters show that \
the transition rates, like the Wigner function itself, can be negative, so \
even this real ",
 Cell[BoxData[
  StyleBox["R", "TI"]], "InlineFormula",
  FontSize->0.9 Inherited,ExpressionUUID->
  "34ce648f-4ca3-483b-a1a9-54eed728e3ae"],
 " need not have the nonnegative off-diagonal rates a genuine phase-space \
transport process would require. In general ",
 Cell[BoxData[
  StyleBox["R", "TI"]], "InlineFormula",
  FontSize->0.9 Inherited,ExpressionUUID->
  "4c14bba7-1748-41b8-8e17-935639a0e0c0"],
 " is complex as well."
}], "Text",ExpressionUUID->"43b67ca0-3c29-450d-bc42-8d2b3101921d"],

Cell[TextData[{
 "Now integrate the motion on the grid. The Wigner function is a real \
nine-vector ",
 Cell[BoxData[
  StyleBox["W", "TI"]], "InlineFormula",
  FontSize->0.9 Inherited,ExpressionUUID->
  "bc96ab24-9eca-440b-b62f-7b336c92df81"],
 ", and the generator propagates it by the linear flow ",
 Cell[BoxData[
  RowBox[{
   StyleBox["W", "TI"], 
   StyleBox["(",
    SpanMaxSize->1], 
   StyleBox["t", "TI"], 
   StyleBox[")",
    SpanMaxSize->1], "=", 
   SuperscriptBox[
    StyleBox["e", "TI"], 
    StyleBox[
     RowBox[{"R", "t"}], "TI"]], " ", 
   StyleBox["W", "TI"], 
   StyleBox["(",
    SpanMaxSize->1], "0", 
   StyleBox[")",
    SpanMaxSize->1]}]], "InlineFormula",
  FontSize->0.9 Inherited,ExpressionUUID->
  "0d3b65b2-269c-4eeb-ab3a-5184578ebb81"],
 ". Evolve ",
 Cell[BoxData[
  TemplateBox[{"0"},
   "Ket"]], "InlineFormula",
  FontSize->0.9 Inherited,ExpressionUUID->
  "21489aaf-20b1-4b54-8b8b-bacb9afe711d"],
 " to ",
 Cell[BoxData[
  RowBox[{
   StyleBox["t", "TI"], "=", "1"}]], "InlineFormula",
  FontSize->0.9 Inherited,ExpressionUUID->
  "6ed6a2a5-2883-447f-a106-553b7882ca64"],
 " and check that probability is conserved on the grid:"
}], "Text",ExpressionUUID->"6d373d6b-5c74-4826-ad03-4f4414f28b05"],

Cell[CellGroupData[{

Cell[BoxData[{
 RowBox[{
  RowBox[{"W0", " ", "=", " ", 
   RowBox[{"Flatten", "[", 
    RowBox[{"N", "[", 
     RowBox[{
      RowBox[{"QuantumState", "[", 
       RowBox[{
        RowBox[{"{", 
         RowBox[{"1", ",", " ", "0", ",", " ", "0"}], "}"}], ",", " ", "3"}], 
       "]"}], "[", "\"\<QuasiProbability\>\"", "]"}], "]"}], "]"}]}], ";"}], "\n", 
 RowBox[{
  RowBox[{"Wt", " ", "=", " ", 
   RowBox[{
    RowBox[{"MatrixExp", "[", "rate", "]"}], " ", ".", " ", "W0"}]}], ";"}], "\n", 
 RowBox[{"Total", "[", "Wt", "]"}]}], "Input",
 CellLabel->
  "In[25]:= ",ExpressionUUID->"02e15963-1bc2-4a4f-bce8-a75eda7d3e26"],

Cell[BoxData["0.9999999999999999`"], "Output",
 CellLabel->
  "Out[25]= ",ExpressionUUID->"4cdf69e9-3724-4909-8b81-6c649a9a4b11"]
}, Open  ]],

Cell[TextData[{
 "The total is ",
 Cell[BoxData["1"], "InlineFormula",
  FontSize->0.9 Inherited,ExpressionUUID->
  "af846dd1-b932-46a0-a2fc-8e1dc41496c2"],
 ": the flow ",
 Cell[BoxData[
  SuperscriptBox[
   StyleBox["e", "TI"], 
   StyleBox[
    RowBox[{"R", "t"}], "TI"]]], "InlineFormula",
  FontSize->0.9 Inherited,ExpressionUUID->
  "85cb2d1c-7715-4b08-858d-5d9b43c991b7"],
 " keeps the Wigner vector normalized, as any legitimate phase-space \
evolution must. Map the evolved vector back to a density matrix with the Weyl \
transform and compare against direct Schr\[ODoubleDot]dinger evolution:"
}], "Text",ExpressionUUID->"154c47f1-3d00-4924-9159-5638f437e17d"],

Cell[CellGroupData[{

Cell[BoxData[{
 RowBox[{
  RowBox[{"onGrid", " ", "=", " ", 
   RowBox[{"QuantumWeylTransform", "[", 
    RowBox[{"QuantumState", "[", 
     RowBox[{"Wt", ",", " ", 
      RowBox[{"QuantumBasis", "[", 
       RowBox[{"\"\<Wigner\>\"", "[", "3", "]"}], "]"}]}], "]"}], "]"}]}], 
  ";"}], "\n", 
 RowBox[{
  RowBox[{"exact", " ", "=", " ", 
   RowBox[{"QuantumState", "[", 
    RowBox[{
     RowBox[{
      RowBox[{"MatrixExp", "[", 
       RowBox[{
        RowBox[{"-", "I"}], " ", 
        RowBox[{"N", "[", 
         RowBox[{"Hq", "[", "\"\<Matrix\>\"", "]"}], "]"}]}], "]"}], " ", ".",
       " ", 
      RowBox[{"{", 
       RowBox[{"1", ",", " ", "0", ",", " ", "0"}], "}"}]}], ",", " ", "3"}], 
    "]"}]}], ";"}], "\n", 
 RowBox[{"Norm", "[", 
  RowBox[{
   RowBox[{"Normal", "[", 
    RowBox[{"onGrid", "[", "\"\<DensityMatrix\>\"", "]"}], "]"}], " ", "-", 
   " ", 
   RowBox[{"exact", "[", "\"\<DensityMatrix\>\"", "]"}]}], "]"}]}], "Input",
 CellLabel->
  "In[26]:= ",ExpressionUUID->"edcbd03d-f893-45fd-8aa1-e87206139a32"],

Cell[BoxData["3.150647214931592`*^-16"], "Output",
 CellLabel->
  "Out[26]= ",ExpressionUUID->"ff92bad4-b8f5-4754-9d4b-3ed088497dc8"]
}, Open  ]],

Cell[TextData[{
 "The two agree to machine precision (",
 Cell[BoxData[
  RowBox[{"\[Tilde]", 
   SuperscriptBox["10", 
    RowBox[{"-", "16"}]]}]], "InlineFormula",
  FontSize->0.9 Inherited,ExpressionUUID->
  "543464e7-1805-49e2-9094-8eb815ea859b"],
 "): the dynamics computed as a flow on the discrete Wigner grid is the Schr\
\[ODoubleDot]dinger equation, expressed in phase-space language. One idiom \
worth flagging: it is the generator ",
 Cell[BoxData[
  StyleBox["R", "TI"]], "InlineFormula",
  FontSize->0.9 Inherited,ExpressionUUID->
  "a1238cd2-62da-4c4c-a3dd-92cbc60868f4"],
 ", applied as ",
 Cell[BoxData[
  SuperscriptBox[
   StyleBox["e", "TI"], 
   StyleBox[
    RowBox[{"R", "t"}], "TI"]]], "InlineFormula",
  FontSize->0.9 Inherited,ExpressionUUID->
  "e3c58a52-1d01-4726-9d14-d9281fc77e09"],
 ", that drives the grid here; the state-level ",
 Cell[BoxData["QuantumEvolve"], "InlineFormula",
  FontSize->0.9 Inherited,ExpressionUUID->
  "67fbddda-eb8c-4e08-9d62-1abca5e50bf4"],
 " wrapper handed a Wigner-picture state does not yet propagate it, so the \
generator route above is the one to use."
}], "Text",ExpressionUUID->"762a0484-8132-496c-b9c9-325cf7bf6ad5"],

Cell[TextData[{
 "The construction extends to open systems. Each jump operator gets its own \
rate matrix through ",
 Cell[BoxData["LindbladTransitionRates"], "InlineFormula",
  FontSize->0.9 Inherited,ExpressionUUID->
  "e903b46e-0e69-4493-a999-a5678e354703"],
 ", and the full open-system generator is the Hamiltonian rate plus the jump \
rates, ",
 Cell[BoxData[
  RowBox[{
   StyleBox["G", "TI"], "=", 
   SubscriptBox[
    StyleBox["R", "TI"], 
    StyleBox["H", "TI"]], "+", 
   UnderscriptBox["\[Sum]", 
    StyleBox["k", "TI"],
    LimitsPositioning->False], 
   SubscriptBox[
    StyleBox["\[Gamma]", "TI"], 
    StyleBox["k", "TI"]], 
   SubscriptBox[
    StyleBox["R", "TI"], 
    SubscriptBox[
     StyleBox["L", "TI"], 
     StyleBox["k", "TI"]]]}]], "InlineFormula",
  FontSize->0.9 Inherited,ExpressionUUID->
  "560ca9bb-9adf-4c7e-bb6f-8f01dfb79d6d"],
 ", still acting on the same nine-component Wigner vector. Build that \
generator for a decaying qutrit, the lowering jump ",
 Cell[BoxData[
  RowBox[{
   StyleBox["L", "TI"], "=", 
   RowBox[{
    RowBox[{
     TemplateBox[{"0"},
      "Ket"], 
     TemplateBox[{"1"},
      "Bra"]}], "+", 
    RowBox[{
     TemplateBox[{"1"},
      "Ket"], 
     TemplateBox[{"2"},
      "Bra"]}]}]}]], "InlineFormula",
  FontSize->0.9 Inherited,ExpressionUUID->
  "ad729e69-446a-47a2-b016-40b4e783a851"],
 " with ",
 Cell[BoxData[
  RowBox[{
   StyleBox["H", "TI"], "=", "0"}]], "InlineFormula",
  FontSize->0.9 Inherited,ExpressionUUID->
  "e3c25790-cd52-4125-856a-0bbfbf1d2a54"],
 " and rate ",
 Cell[BoxData["1"], "InlineFormula",
  FontSize->0.9 Inherited,ExpressionUUID->
  "17f68586-5faa-4f59-9969-433a7b5b4007"],
 ", and evolve ",
 Cell[BoxData[
  TemplateBox[{"2"},
   "Ket"]], "InlineFormula",
  FontSize->0.9 Inherited,ExpressionUUID->
  "bba54e2e-41cf-415c-94fc-e99988f2eaec"],
 " on the grid to ",
 Cell[BoxData[
  RowBox[{
   StyleBox["t", "TI"], "=", "1"}]], "InlineFormula",
  FontSize->0.9 Inherited,ExpressionUUID->
  "fb2ca4d9-c081-48a2-97de-a8c5ed4e7f8c"],
 ":"
}], "Text",ExpressionUUID->"ad3b6824-de27-452f-a58e-471f104ace25"],

Cell[CellGroupData[{

Cell[BoxData[{
 RowBox[{
  RowBox[{"Lop", " ", "=", " ", 
   RowBox[{"QuantumOperator", "[", 
    RowBox[{
     RowBox[{"{", 
      RowBox[{
       RowBox[{"{", 
        RowBox[{"0", ",", " ", "1", ",", " ", "0"}], "}"}], ",", " ", 
       RowBox[{"{", 
        RowBox[{"0", ",", " ", "0", ",", " ", "1"}], "}"}], ",", " ", 
       RowBox[{"{", 
        RowBox[{"0", ",", " ", "0", ",", " ", "0"}], "}"}]}], "}"}], ",", " ", 
     RowBox[{"{", "1", "}"}]}], "]"}]}], ";"}], "\n", 
 RowBox[{
  RowBox[{"Hz", " ", "=", " ", 
   RowBox[{"QuantumOperator", "[", 
    RowBox[{
     RowBox[{"ConstantArray", "[", 
      RowBox[{"0", ",", " ", 
       RowBox[{"{", 
        RowBox[{"3", ",", " ", "3"}], "}"}]}], "]"}], ",", " ", 
     RowBox[{"{", "1", "}"}]}], "]"}]}], ";"}], "\n", 
 RowBox[{
  RowBox[{"G", " ", "=", " ", 
   RowBox[{
    RowBox[{"HamiltonianTransitionRate", "[", "Hz", "]"}], " ", "+", " ", 
    RowBox[{"Total", " ", "@", " ", 
     RowBox[{"LindbladTransitionRates", "[", 
      RowBox[{"{", "Lop", "}"}], "]"}]}]}]}], ";"}], "\n", 
 RowBox[{
  RowBox[{"Wd", " ", "=", " ", 
   RowBox[{
    RowBox[{"MatrixExp", "[", "G", "]"}], " ", ".", " ", 
    RowBox[{"Flatten", "[", 
     RowBox[{"N", "[", 
      RowBox[{
       RowBox[{"QuantumState", "[", 
        RowBox[{
         RowBox[{"{", 
          RowBox[{"0", ",", " ", "0", ",", " ", "1"}], "}"}], ",", " ", "3"}],
         "]"}], "[", "\"\<QuasiProbability\>\"", "]"}], "]"}], "]"}]}]}], 
  ";"}], "\n", 
 RowBox[{"Total", "[", "Wd", "]"}]}], "Input",
 CellLabel->
  "In[27]:= ",ExpressionUUID->"8ebdf90f-31f3-4f30-974b-ccee73494441"],

Cell[BoxData["0.9999999999999999`"], "Output",
 CellLabel->
  "Out[27]= ",ExpressionUUID->"565db848-07e2-4ef5-bc96-055e651988d5"]
}, Open  ]],

Cell[TextData[{
 "The total is again ",
 Cell[BoxData["1"], "InlineFormula",
  FontSize->0.9 Inherited,ExpressionUUID->
  "a4045a21-feb7-43c7-8200-5c558758057b"],
 ": the dissipative flow is trace-preserving on the grid. Map the evolved \
Wigner vector back and compare against a direct integration of the Lindblad \
master equation, where the rule-form signature ",
 Cell[BoxData[
  RowBox[{"{", 
   StyleBox["L", "TI"], "}", "\[Rule]", "{", 
   StyleBox["\[Gamma]", "TI"], "}"}]], "InlineFormula",
  FontSize->0.9 Inherited,ExpressionUUID->
  "412d60c3-828c-4776-bfd7-ba95b05a6368"],
 " pairs each jump operator with its rate (the positional form does not \
converge here):"
}], "Text",ExpressionUUID->"4db2cd08-dec7-4c87-846d-60b8405f4872"],

Cell[CellGroupData[{

Cell[BoxData[{
 RowBox[{
  RowBox[{"openGrid", " ", "=", " ", 
   RowBox[{"QuantumWeylTransform", "[", 
    RowBox[{"QuantumState", "[", 
     RowBox[{"Wd", ",", " ", 
      RowBox[{"QuantumBasis", "[", 
       RowBox[{"\"\<Wigner\>\"", "[", "3", "]"}], "]"}]}], "]"}], "]"}]}], 
  ";"}], "\n", 
 RowBox[{
  RowBox[{"exactOpen", " ", "=", " ", 
   RowBox[{"QuantumEvolve", "[", 
    RowBox[{"Hz", ",", " ", 
     RowBox[{
      RowBox[{"{", "Lop", "}"}], " ", "->", " ", 
      RowBox[{"{", "1", "}"}]}], ",", " ", 
     RowBox[{"QuantumState", "[", 
      RowBox[{
       RowBox[{"{", 
        RowBox[{"0", ",", " ", "0", ",", " ", "1"}], "}"}], ",", " ", "3"}], 
      "]"}], ",", " ", 
     RowBox[{"{", 
      RowBox[{"t", ",", " ", "0", ",", " ", "1"}], "}"}]}], "]"}]}], ";"}], "\n", 
 RowBox[{"Norm", "[", 
  RowBox[{
   RowBox[{"Normal", "[", 
    RowBox[{"openGrid", "[", "\"\<DensityMatrix\>\"", "]"}], "]"}], " ", "-", 
   " ", 
   RowBox[{"(", 
    RowBox[{
     RowBox[{"Normal", "[", 
      RowBox[{"exactOpen", "[", "\"\<DensityMatrix\>\"", "]"}], "]"}], " ", "/.",
      " ", 
     RowBox[{"t", " ", "->", " ", "1."}]}], ")"}]}], "]"}]}], "Input",
 CellLabel->
  "In[28]:= ",ExpressionUUID->"d9e04c63-d207-4050-8787-f71309ff696c"],

Cell[BoxData["4.89567730799223`*^-9"], "Output",
 CellLabel->
  "Out[28]= ",ExpressionUUID->"96064962-e63b-477f-b601-e83b2e8dc08c"]
}, Open  ]],

Cell[TextData[{
 "The grid-evolved dissipative state matches the directly integrated master \
equation to solver tolerance (",
 Cell[BoxData[
  RowBox[{"\[Tilde]", 
   SuperscriptBox["10", 
    RowBox[{"-", "9"}]]}]], "InlineFormula",
  FontSize->0.9 Inherited,ExpressionUUID->
  "d5cd66de-581c-489e-8183-009d9fad4626"],
 "). Closed or open, the phase-space picture carries a genuine generator on \
the discrete grid: the Braasch-Wootters rate matrix ",
 Cell[BoxData[
  SubscriptBox[
   StyleBox["R", "TI"], 
   StyleBox["H", "TI"]]], "InlineFormula",
  FontSize->0.9 Inherited,ExpressionUUID->
  "31942119-49d0-418a-9253-04bea6c008a5"],
 " for the unitary part, and ",
 Cell[BoxData["LindbladTransitionRates"], "InlineFormula",
  FontSize->0.9 Inherited,ExpressionUUID->
  "eb338200-7369-41a6-be5b-67f0e1f263b3"],
 " for the dissipative part."
}], "Text",ExpressionUUID->"c11c7be0-4bd6-43bd-8672-cb0e38f6fec6"],

Cell["Where this leaves us", "Section",ExpressionUUID->"9f05b406-9f0a-4813-8fd0-b903cb7aba18"],

Cell["\<\
We built the finite phase-space formalism from the ground up and, at every \
step, computed rather than asserted. In order:\
\>", "Text",ExpressionUUID->"53ff5c5c-37d2-4998-8f51-c359355b5865"],

Cell[TextData[{
 "The ",
 StyleBox["Heisenberg-Weyl group",
  FontWeight->"Bold"],
 " (clock ",
 Cell[BoxData[
  StyleBox["Z", "TI"]], "InlineFormula",
  FontSize->0.9 Inherited,ExpressionUUID->
  "907ac100-aff5-4143-8882-40caea8240b1"],
 ", shift ",
 Cell[BoxData[
  StyleBox["X", "TI"]], "InlineFormula",
  FontSize->0.9 Inherited,ExpressionUUID->
  "7e8062b4-81fe-4bdb-942f-9df67ae6bf3f"],
 ", displacements ",
 Cell[BoxData[
  RowBox[{
   StyleBox["D", "TI"], 
   StyleBox["(",
    SpanMaxSize->1], 
   RowBox[{
    StyleBox["a", "TI"], ",", 
    StyleBox["b", "TI"]}], 
   StyleBox[")",
    SpanMaxSize->1]}]], "InlineFormula",
  FontSize->0.9 Inherited,ExpressionUUID->
  "f224551c-5ec5-456b-b7d9-b9c77715791b"],
 ") is the finite analogue of position and momentum, defined by the one \
relation ",
 Cell[BoxData[
  RowBox[{
   StyleBox["Z", "TI"], 
   StyleBox["X", "TI"], "=", 
   StyleBox["\[Omega]", "TI"], 
   StyleBox["X", "TI"], 
   StyleBox["Z", "TI"]}]], "InlineFormula",
  FontSize->0.9 Inherited,ExpressionUUID->
  "78396305-26a4-401a-8b88-be9eca85ef1b"],
 "."
}], "Item",ExpressionUUID->"02a56a97-51b3-461c-aa04-a47a31905254"],

Cell[TextData[{
 "The ",
 StyleBox["discrete Wigner function",
  FontWeight->"Bold"],
 " ",
 Cell[BoxData[
  RowBox[{
   SubscriptBox[
    StyleBox["W", "TI"], 
    StyleBox["\[Rho]", "TI"]], 
   StyleBox["(",
    SpanMaxSize->1], 
   RowBox[{
    StyleBox["q", "TI"], ",", 
    StyleBox["p", "TI"]}], 
   StyleBox[")",
    SpanMaxSize->1], "=", 
   FractionBox["1", 
    StyleBox["d", "TI"]], 
   StyleBox["Tr",
    FontSlant->"Plain"], 
   StyleBox["[",
    SpanMaxSize->1], 
   RowBox[{
    StyleBox["\[Rho]", "TI"], 
    StyleBox["A", "TI"], 
    StyleBox["(",
     SpanMaxSize->1], 
    RowBox[{
     StyleBox["q", "TI"], ",", 
     StyleBox["p", "TI"]}], 
    StyleBox[")",
     SpanMaxSize->1]}], 
   StyleBox["]",
    SpanMaxSize->1]}]], "InlineFormula",
  FontSize->0.9 Inherited,ExpressionUUID->
  "c0f87d72-2d2d-41ed-9430-8335e0416be0"],
 " is a faithful, invertible re-encoding of a state whose marginals are the \
measurement probabilities."
}], "Item",ExpressionUUID->"8123ae12-1add-49bd-ad2f-c46c40efd146"],

Cell[TextData[{
 StyleBox["Negativity",
  FontWeight->"Bold"],
 " of ",
 Cell[BoxData[
  StyleBox["W", "TI"]], "InlineFormula",
  FontSize->0.9 Inherited,ExpressionUUID->
  "68527e42-d2a7-442c-8ca5-1303c2dbbe35"],
 " is a computable signature that ties several statements together: it marks \
non-stabilizer states (the discrete Hudson theorem, odd ",
 Cell[BoxData[
  StyleBox["d", "TI"]], "InlineFormula",
  FontSize->0.9 Inherited,ExpressionUUID->
  "eb86f4f7-e0e4-42ff-adbd-5de3b1c2850d"],
 "), it is quantified by ",
 StyleBox["mana",
  FontWeight->"Bold"],
 " as an odd-",
 Cell[BoxData[
  StyleBox["d", "TI"]], "InlineFormula",
  FontSize->0.9 Inherited,ExpressionUUID->
  "e8993b8e-5d2a-49b6-b133-46618a168ead"],
 " magic monotone, it sets the ",
 StyleBox["cost of classical simulation",
  FontWeight->"Bold"],
 " (the sampling overhead ",
 Cell[BoxData[
  RowBox[{"\[Tilde]", 
   SuperscriptBox[
    StyleBox["e", "TI"], 
    RowBox[{"2", "\[ScriptCapitalM]"}]]}]], "InlineFormula",
  FontSize->0.9 Inherited,ExpressionUUID->
  "c64cb605-3888-47c5-84b6-923b5ebef396"],
 ", free in the nonnegative Gottesman-Knill regime), and, by Spekkens' \
equivalence, it is a signature of ",
 StyleBox["contextuality",
  FontWeight->"Bold"],
 "."
}], "Item",ExpressionUUID->"f0e16940-3742-4d7c-b13a-2e7274db2207"],

Cell[TextData[{
 StyleBox["SIC",
  FontWeight->"Bold"],
 " and ",
 StyleBox["MIC",
  FontWeight->"Bold"],
 " measurements are alternative frames for the same operator space, minimal \
and informationally complete, underlying the QBist reconstruction of the Born \
rule."
}], "Item",ExpressionUUID->"8fd4f6a4-784e-4a60-9f35-116270ad036b"],

Cell[TextData[{
 StyleBox["Mutually unbiased bases",
  FontWeight->"Bold"],
 " are the optimal set of complementary measurements, ",
 Cell[BoxData[
  RowBox[{
   StyleBox["d", "TI"], "+", "1"}]], "InlineFormula",
  FontSize->0.9 Inherited,ExpressionUUID->
  "ab4197da-074c-46b3-bb28-cfa03171a828"],
 " of them for prime-power ",
 Cell[BoxData[
  StyleBox["d", "TI"]], "InlineFormula",
  FontSize->0.9 Inherited,ExpressionUUID->
  "54db7eed-3905-4a7e-8514-44b1636dd505"],
 "."
}], "Item",ExpressionUUID->"f4a9e828-f995-4039-bc6d-36baeda2889b"],

Cell[TextData[{
 "The ",
 StyleBox["Weyl transform",
  FontWeight->"Bold"],
 " inverts the Wigner map exactly, and the ",
 StyleBox["Braasch-Wootters transition-rate generator",
  FontWeight->"Bold"],
 " ",
 Cell[BoxData[
  RowBox[{
   OverscriptBox[
    StyleBox["W", "TI"], "."], "=", 
   StyleBox["R", "TI"], " ", 
   StyleBox["W", "TI"]}]], "InlineFormula",
  FontSize->0.9 Inherited,ExpressionUUID->
  "2a9af15c-0116-45d7-8793-7d957118c82f"],
 " propagates the Wigner vector on the grid: closed evolution as the flow ",
 Cell[BoxData[
  SuperscriptBox[
   StyleBox["e", "TI"], 
   StyleBox[
    RowBox[{"R", "t"}], "TI"]]], "InlineFormula",
  FontSize->0.9 Inherited,ExpressionUUID->
  "1ac0aa0c-7183-4eb1-b434-b142fd2a8ad7"],
 " reproduces Schr\[ODoubleDot]dinger to machine precision, and the open \
(dissipative) case, with ",
 Cell[BoxData["LindbladTransitionRates"], "InlineFormula",
  FontSize->0.9 Inherited,ExpressionUUID->
  "8f0699f9-6fbc-48f3-937b-bd753ccd4a74"],
 " supplying the jump rates, matches the directly integrated master \
equation."
}], "Item",ExpressionUUID->"aa6c7d93-5429-4bde-9963-29e706445f50"],

Cell[TextData[{
 "What makes this more than a change of notation is that each classical \
result became an executable check: Hudson's theorem is a comparison of two ",
 Cell[BoxData["Min"], "InlineFormula",
  FontSize->0.9 Inherited,ExpressionUUID->
  "c7919e9f-ba6a-48bd-9e85-233317b74be3"],
 " values, mana is a one-line functional of a table, and the Braasch-Wootters \
generator, applied as ",
 Cell[BoxData[
  SuperscriptBox[
   StyleBox["e", "TI"], 
   StyleBox[
    RowBox[{"R", "t"}], "TI"]]], "InlineFormula",
  FontSize->0.9 Inherited,ExpressionUUID->
  "392bdc35-23ca-4d51-a6bd-5e5519bc09cf"],
 ", reproduces Schr\[ODoubleDot]dinger evolution on the grid to machine \
precision. One boundary is worth remembering: the odd-dimensional machinery \
is exact and covariant, and it is where the on-grid evolution above runs \
cleanly; the even-dimensional qubit case rides on the doubled ",
 Cell[BoxData[
  RowBox[{"2", 
   StyleBox["d", "TI"], "\[Times]", "2", 
   StyleBox["d", "TI"]}]], "InlineFormula",
  FontSize->0.9 Inherited,ExpressionUUID->
  "58e98c12-36c5-4540-9144-ae1a1f095613"],
 " grid, whose read-back is not canonical, and the state-level ",
 Cell[BoxData["QuantumEvolve"], "InlineFormula",
  FontSize->0.9 Inherited,ExpressionUUID->
  "62080976-c88c-44e4-9723-9d35ccf9060d"],
 " phase-space wrapper does not yet drive the grid (the generator route \
does). With those caveats, the phase-space picture is a working laboratory \
for finite-dimensional quantum mechanics, and the same tools scale straight \
to multi-qudit systems and to the resource theories built on negativity."
}], "Text",ExpressionUUID->"5d045126-9309-4637-aa34-f623f415e95d"],

Cell["References", "Section",ExpressionUUID->"71a08063-36ed-43ec-89af-a481f394fb50"],

